# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protobuf-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The CPU in modern computer hardware performs reads and writes to memory most efficiently when the data is *naturally aligned*, which generally means that the data's memory address is a multiple of the data size.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For instance, in a 32-bit architecture, the data may be aligned if the data is stored in four consecutive bytes and the first byte lies on a 4-byte boundary.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Although data structure alignment is a fundamental issue for all modern computers, many programming languages and programming language implementations handle data alignment automatically.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Fortran, Ada, PL/I, Pascal, certain C and C++ implementations, D, Rust, C#, and assembly language allow at least partial control of data structure padding, which may be useful in certain special circumstances.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A memory address *a* is said to be *n-byte aligned* when *a* is a multiple of *n* (where *n* is a power of 2).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] In this context, a byte is the smallest unit of memory access, i.e. each memory address specifies a different byte.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] An *n*-byte aligned address would have a minimum of log2(*n*) least-significant zeros when expressed in binary.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The alternate wording *b-bit aligned* designates a *b/8 byte aligned* address (ex.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A memory access is said to be *aligned* when the data being accessed is *n* bytes long and the datum address is *n*-byte aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] When a memory access is not aligned, it is said to be *misaligned*.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Note that by definition byte memory accesses are always aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A memory pointer that refers to primitive data that is *n* bytes long is said to be *aligned* if it is only allowed to contain addresses that are *n*-byte aligned, otherwise it is said to be *unaligned*.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A memory pointer that refers to a data aggregate (a data structure or array) is *aligned* if (and only if) each primitive datum in the aggregate is aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Note that the definitions above assume that each primitive datum is a power of two bytes long.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] When this is not the case (as with 80-bit floating-point on x86) the context influences the conditions where the datum is considered aligned or not.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Data structures can be stored in memory on the stack with a static size known as *bounded* or on the heap with a dynamic size known as *unbounded*.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The CPU accesses memory by a single memory word at a time.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] As long as the memory word size is at least as large as the largest primitive data type supported by the computer, aligned accesses will always access a single memory word.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This may not be true for misaligned data accesses.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] If the highest and lowest bytes in a datum are not within the same memory word, the computer must split the datum access into multiple memory accesses.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This requires a lot of complex circuitry to generate the memory accesses and coordinate them.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] To handle the case where the memory words are in different memory pages the processor must either verify that both pages are present before executing the instruction or be able to handle a TLB miss or a page fault on any memory access during the instruction execution.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Some processor designs deliberately avoid introducing such complexity, and instead yield alternative behavior in the event of a misaligned memory access.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For example, implementations of the ARM architecture prior to the ARMv6 ISA require mandatory aligned memory access for all multi-byte load and store instructions.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The ARMv6 and later architectures support unaligned access in many circumstances, but not necessarily all.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] When a single memory word is accessed the operation is atomic, i.e. the whole memory word is read or written at once and other devices must wait until the read or write operation completes before they can access it.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This may not be true for unaligned accesses to multiple memory words, e.g. the first word might be read by one device, both words written by another device and then the second word read by the first device so that the value read is neither the original value nor the updated value.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Although such failures are rare, they can be very difficult to identify.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Although the compiler (or interpreter) normally allocates individual data items on aligned boundaries, data structures often have members with different alignment requirements.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] To maintain proper alignment the translator normally inserts additional unnamed data members so that each member is properly aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] In addition, the data structure as a whole may be padded with a final unnamed member.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This allows each member of an array of structures to be properly aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Padding is only inserted when a structure member is followed by a member with a larger alignment requirement or at the end of the structure.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] By changing the ordering of members in a structure, it is possible to change the amount of padding required to maintain alignment.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For example, if members are sorted by descending alignment requirements a minimal amount of padding is required.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The minimal amount of padding required is always less than the largest alignment in the structure.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Computing the maximum amount of padding required is more complicated, but is always less than the sum of the alignment requirements for all members minus twice the sum of the alignment requirements for the least aligned half of the structure members.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Although C and C++ do not allow the compiler to reorder structure members to save space, other languages might.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] It is also possible to tell most C and C++ compilers to "pack" the members of a structure to a certain level of alignment, e.g.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] "pack(2)" means align data members larger than a byte to a two-byte boundary so that any padding members are at most one byte long.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Likewise, in PL/I a structure may be declared `UNALIGNED` to eliminate all padding except around bit strings.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] One use for such "packed" structures is to conserve memory.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For example, a structure containing a single byte (such as a `char`) and a four-byte integer (such as `uint32_t`) would require three additional bytes of padding.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A large array of such structures would use 37.5% less memory if they are packed, although accessing each structure might take longer.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This compromise may be considered a form of space–time tradeoff.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Although use of "packed" structures is most frequently used to conserve memory space, it may also be used to format a data structure for transmission using a standard protocol.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] However, in this usage, care must also be taken to ensure that the values of the struct members are stored with the endianness required by the protocol (often network byte order), which may be different from the endianness used natively by the host machine.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For example, the padding to add to offset 0x59d for a 4-byte aligned structure is 3.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The structure will then start at 0x5a0, which is a multiple of 4.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] However, when the alignment of *offset* is already equal to that of *align*, the second modulo in *(align - (offset mod align)) mod align* will return zero, therefore the original value is left unchanged.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Since the alignment is by definition a power of two, the modulo operation can be reduced to a bitwise AND operation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] If the type `short` is stored in two bytes of memory then each member of the data structure depicted above would be 2-byte aligned.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] `data1` would be at offset 0, `data2` at offset 2, and `data3` at offset 4.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The size of this structure would be 6 bytes.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The type of each member of the structure usually has a default alignment, meaning that it will, unless otherwise requested by the programmer, be aligned on a pre-determined boundary.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Some data types are dependent on the implementation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The compiled size of the structure is now 12 bytes.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The last member is padded with the number of bytes required so that the total size of the structure should be a multiple of the largest alignment of any structure member (alignof(int) in this case, which = 4 on linux-32bit/gcc).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] In this case 3 bytes are added to the last member to pad the structure to the size of 12 bytes (alignof(int) * 3).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] In this example the total size of the structure sizeof(FinalPad) == 8, not 5 (so that the size is a multiple of 4 (alignof(float))).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] In this example the total size of the structure sizeof(FinalPadShort) == 6, not 5 (not 8 either) (so that the size is a multiple of 2 (alignof(short) == 2 on linux-32bit/gcc)).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] It is possible to change the alignment of structures to reduce the memory they require (or to conform to an existing format) by reordering structure members or changing the compiler's alignment (or “packing”) of structure members.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The compiled size of the structure now matches the pre-compiled size of **8 bytes**.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Note that padding1[1] has been replaced (and thus eliminated) by data4 and padding2[3] is no longer necessary as the structure is already aligned to the size of a long word.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The alternative method of enforcing the MixedData structure to be aligned to a one byte boundary will cause the pre-processor to discard the pre-determined alignment of the structure members and thus no padding bytes would be inserted.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] While there is no standard way of defining the alignment of structure members (while C and C++ allow using the alignas specifier for this purpose it can be used only for specifying a stricter alignment), some compilers use #pragma directives to specify packing inside source files.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This structure would have a compiled size of **6 bytes** on a 32-bit system.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The above directives are available in compilers from Microsoft, Borland, GNU, and many others.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] On some Microsoft compilers, particularly for RISC processors, there is an unexpected relationship between project default packing (the /Zp directive) and the #pragma pack directive.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The #pragma pack directive can only be used to **reduce** the packing size of a structure from the project default packing.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This leads to interoperability problems with library headers which use, for example, #pragma pack(8), if the project packing is smaller than this.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For this reason, setting the project packing to any value other than the default of 8 bytes would break the #pragma pack directives used in library headers and result in binary incompatibilities between structures.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This limitation is not present when compiling for x86.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] It would be beneficial to allocate memory aligned to cache lines.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] If an array is partitioned for more than one thread to operate on, having the sub-array boundaries unaligned to cache lines could lead to performance degradation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Here is an example to allocate memory (double array of size 10) aligned to cache of 64 bytes.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Alignment concerns can affect areas much larger than a C structure when the purpose is the efficient mapping of that area through a hardware address translation mechanism (PCI remapping, operation of a MMU).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] For instance, on a 32-bit operating system, a 4 KiB (4096 bytes) page is not just an arbitrary 4 KiB chunk of data.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Instead, it is usually a region of memory that is aligned on a 4 KiB boundary.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This is because aligning a page on a page-sized boundary lets the hardware map a virtual address to a physical address by substituting the higher bits in the address, rather than doing complex arithmetic.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Example: Assume that we have a TLB mapping of virtual address 0x2CFC7000 to physical address 0x12345000.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] (Note that both these addresses are aligned at 4 KiB boundaries.) Accessing data located at virtual address va=0x2CFC7ABC causes a TLB resolution of 0x2CFC7 to 0x12345 to issue a physical access to {{{1}}}.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] Here, the 20/12-bit split luckily matches the hexadecimal representation split at 5/3 digits.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] The hardware can implement this translation by simply combining the first 20 bits of the physical address (0x12345) and the last 12 bits of the virtual address (0xABC).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This is also referred to as virtually indexed (ABC) physically tagged (12345).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] A block of data of size 2(n+1) − 1 always has one sub-block of size 2n aligned on 2n bytes.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] This is how a dynamic allocator that has no knowledge of alignment, can be used to provide aligned buffers, at the price of a factor two in space loss.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/data-structure-alignment] where `ALIGN_TO_NEXT(*p*, *r*)` works by adding an aligned increment, then clearing the `*r*` least significant bits of `*p*`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
