[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
