[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
