[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] In computer networking, a **wire protocol** refers to a way of getting data from point to point: A wire protocol is needed if more than one application has to interoperate.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] It generally refers to communication protocols higher than the physical layer.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] In contrast to transport protocols at the transport level (like TCP or UDP), the term *wire protocol* is used to describe a common way to exchange information at the application level.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] It refers to an application layer protocol and defines all the required attributes for the data exchange, like data types (units of data, message formats, etc.), communication endpoints and capabilities (such as delivery guarantees, direction of communication, etc.).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] Usually, the data is represented at the application level as a common infoset (e.g.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] XML, JSON, YAML) and requires a mechanism of data binding (using e.g. a common encoding scheme like XSD).
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] The wire protocol may be either text-based or a binary protocol.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] Although an important architectural decision, this is a separate matter from the distinction between wire protocols and programmatic APIs.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] In electronics, a wire protocol is the mechanism used to transmit data from one point to another.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] A wire protocol provides the means for the interoperation of one or more applications in a network.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] They often refer to distributed object protocols, or they use applications that were designed to work together.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] As the name suggests, these distributed object protocols run in different processes in one or several computers that are connected over a network.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] Wire protocols provide the means for a program running under one operating system to communicate with a program running under some other operating system over a network such as an organization's intranet or the Internet.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] The protocol thus interconnects multiple platforms.
[src:protobuf-cpp-lib/wire-protocol] Some wire protocols are language-independent, allowing the communication of programs written in different programming languages.
